@endnode "What it is..."
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node whatitis
Mouseki is an on-screen keyboard replacer. It lets you type using the mouse 
without the amiga knowing you're not using the keyboard.

@endnode
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node why "Why?"
Three reasons really.

There are those of us who can't use a keyboard for some reason or other,
Mouseki opens up a whole new world of keyboard driven software such as
languages, word processors and of course, Infocom adventures.

Of course, you may be perfectly able to use your keyboard but find the
amiga isn't (this effect can be achieved by pouring red wine onto the keys
while powered up!). In this situation Mouseki means you can still use the
system while your keyboard is repaired (or you suck it clean).

Or you might own a keyboardless Amiga, such as a CDł˛, in which case 
Mouseki gives you the ability to type.

@endnode
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node howdoidoit "How do I do it?"
It is dead easy. All you do is follow these steps...

1) Put the font in FONTS:
2) Double click on the icon.
3) Click on the window or screen you want to type into.
4) Type.
5) To quit choose Quit from the Config menu.

Mouseki's titlebar will tell you what qualifier keys are active.

See Also -

@{"Active Character Mode" link activecharactermode} for programs that misbehave.
@{"Window or Screen     " link windowscreen} For funny applications.
@{"Text Macros          " link textmacros} For an easy life.

* The font isn't at all vital, but Mouseki looks a lot prettier with it.

@endnode
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node  activecharactermode "Active Character Mode"
Some software, notably that which uses Gadtools, will not allow Mouseki to
type into text gadgets. To help with this problem, Active Character Mode
has been added.

Many Gadtools text gadgets have a hotkey to activate them. Active Character
Mode uses this feature to allow Mouseki to access these gadgets.

To use Active Character Mode, select 'ACM' from the keyboard.  Now select
'Set' from the keyboard, and press the desired key on Mouseki's keyboard.

While Active Character Mode is turned on, every key pressed will be
proceeded by the defined Active Character. For example, using the Active
Character 'x' to enter 'hello' into a text gadget actually types 
'xhxexlxlxo'.

Active Character Mode must be turned off to enable normal keyboard control.
This will not clear the currently set Active Character.

Hint: try using Right Cursor for file requesters. This is the default.

@endnode
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node  windowscreen "Window Or Screen"
By default, Mouseki opens as a custom screen. However, by choosing
'Window/Screen Mode' from the Config menu you can make Mouseki reopen on
the Workbench in a window.

I added this primarily to help with mode promoted screens, but it has also
proved useful for other things, such as RTG graphics cards.

@endnode
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node  textmacros "Text Macros"
Mouseki also has a small 'macro' facility. Commonly used text sequences can
be assigned to a menu.

These sequences can easily be created using a text editor. A template for
the menu file is as follows :-

MTITLE Name Of Menu
MITEM Text To Be Typed 1
MITEM Text To Be Typed 2
MITEM Text To Be Typed 3
MITEM Text To Be Typed 4

There can be upto 10 MTITLES in each file, with upto 6 MITEMS following it.

The text defined after each keyword will be shown in the menu strip exactly
as it appears in the menu file. Similarly, the text will be typed into the
current window exactly as it appears in the menu, regardless of qualifier
keys.

New menus can be loaded by choosing the Load item from the Config menu. The
default menu is found in S:Mouseki.menu.

That's it.


@endnode
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node limitations "Limitations..."
Some (not all) windows with multiple text gadgets on will not accept input
from Mouseki into these gadgets. Others will accept partial input but not
hotkeys. These limitations are caused by the coding of the application, not
Mouseki.

Active Character Mode solves many problems caused by the above limitation.
See @{"Active Character Mode" link activecharactermode} for more information.

@endnode
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node systemrequirements "System Requirements..."
It was written on a 3.0 A4000/40 with 2 meg chip, 8 meg fast and a
GVP ioExtender, and a 3.0 A1200 with 2 meg chip, 4 meg fast and 68030
accelerator. It should run on any 2.0 machine, below that I don't know
and I'm not dismembering my Lorraine to find out!

@endnode
@Remark ------------------------------------------------------------------
@node bugs "Bugs..."
If Mouseki is used to control Acid Software's wonderful Blitz Basic II
v1.7 (or less), compiling code can cause a total system reboot.  Try
quitting Mouseki before compilation.  I am looking into this.  Similarly, a
system lockup has also been caused whilst using TED.  Again, I am checking
on this. I suspect TED is at fault.

@endnode
